aa(lp12
VA hundred years ago,
p13
aVAlbert Einstein first published his theory of general relativity.
p14
aVIn the years since then,
p15
aVscientists have provided a lot of evidence in support of it.
p16
aVBut one thing predicted from this theory, black holes,
p17
aVstill have not been directly observed.
p18
aVAlthough we have some idea as to what a black hole might look like,
p19
aVwe've never actually taken a picture of one before.
p20
aVHowever, you might be surprised to know that that may soon change.
p21
aVWe may be seeing our first picture of a black hole in the next couple years.
p22
aVGetting this first picture will come down to an international team of scientists,
p23
aVan Earth-sized telescope
p24
aVand an algorithm that puts together the final picture.
p25
aVAlthough I won't be able to show you a real picture of a black hole today,
p26
aVI'd like to give you a brief glimpse into the effort involved
p27
aVin getting that first picture.
p28
aa(lp29
VMy name is Katie Bouman,
p30
aVand I'm a PhD student at MIT.
p31
aVI do research in a computer science lab
p32
aVthat works on making computers see through images and video.
p33
aVBut although I'm not an astronomer,
p34
aVtoday I'd like to show you
p35
aVhow I've been able to contribute to this exciting project.
p36
aa(lp37
VIf you go out past the bright city lights tonight,
p38
aVyou may just be lucky enough to see a stunning view
p39
aVof the Milky Way Galaxy.
p40
aVAnd if you could zoom past millions of stars,
p41
aV26,000 light-years toward the heart of the spiraling Milky Way,
p42
aVwe'd eventually reach a cluster of stars right at the center.
p43
aVPeering past all the galactic dust with infrared telescopes,
p44
aVastronomers have watched these stars for over 16 years.
p45
aVBut it's what they don't see that is the most spectacular.
p46
aVThese stars seem to orbit an invisible object.
p47
aVBy tracking the paths of these stars,
p48
aVastronomers have concluded
p49
aVthat the only thing small and heavy enough to cause this motion
p50
aVis a supermassive black hole \u2014
p51
aVan object so dense that it sucks up anything that ventures too close \u2014
p52
aVeven light.
p53
aa(lp54
VBut what happens if we were to zoom in even further?
p55
aVIs it possible to see something that, by definition, is impossible to see?
p56
aVWell, it turns out that if we were to zoom in at radio wavelengths,
p57
aVwe'd expect to see a ring of light
p58
aVcaused by the gravitational lensing of hot plasma
p59
aVzipping around the black hole.
p60
aVIn other words,
p61
aVthe black hole casts a shadow on this backdrop of bright material,
p62
aVcarving out a sphere of darkness.
p63
aVThis bright ring reveals the black hole's event horizon,
p64
aVwhere the gravitational pull becomes so great
p65
aVthat not even light can escape.
p66
aVEinstein's equations predict the size and shape of this ring,
p67
aVso taking a picture of it wouldn't only be really cool,
p68
aVit would also help to verify that these equations hold
p69
aVin the extreme conditions around the black hole.
p70
aa(lp71
VHowever, this black hole is so far away from us,
p72
aVthat from Earth, this ring appears incredibly small \u2014
p73
aVthe same size to us as an orange on the surface of the moon.
p74
aVThat makes taking a picture of it extremely difficult.
p75
aVWhy is that?
p76
aVWell, it all comes down to a simple equation.
p77
aVDue to a phenomenon called diffraction,
p78
aVthere are fundamental limits
p79
aVto the smallest objects that we can possibly see.
p80
aVThis governing equation says that in order to see smaller and smaller,
p81
aVwe need to make our telescope bigger and bigger.
p82
aVBut even with the most powerful optical telescopes here on Earth,
p83
aVwe can't even get close to the resolution necessary
p84
aVto image on the surface of the moon.
p85
aVIn fact, here I show one of the highest resolution images ever taken
p86
aVof the moon from Earth.
p87
aVIt contains roughly 13,000 pixels,
p88
aVand yet each pixel would contain over 1.5 million oranges.
p89
aa(lp90
VSo how big of a telescope do we need
p91
aVin order to see an orange on the surface of the moon
p92
aVand, by extension, our black hole?
p93
aVWell, it turns out that by crunching the numbers,
p94
aVyou can easily calculate that we would need a telescope
p95
aVthe size of the entire Earth.
p96
aa(lp97
V(Laughter)
p98
aa(lp99
VIf we could build this Earth-sized telescope,
p100
aVwe could just start to make out that distinctive ring of light
p101
aVindicative of the black hole's event horizon.
p102
aVAlthough this picture wouldn't contain all the detail we see
p103
aVin computer graphic renderings,
p104
aVit would allow us to safely get our first glimpse
p105
aVof the immediate environment around a black hole.
