aa(lp107
VHowever, as you can imagine,
p108
aVbuilding a single-dish telescope the size of the Earth is impossible.
p109
aVBut in the famous words of Mick Jagger,
p110
aV"You can't always get what you want,
p111
aVbut if you try sometimes, you just might find
p112
aVyou get what you need."
p113
aVAnd by connecting telescopes from around the world,
p114
aVan international collaboration called the Event Horizon Telescope
p115
aVis creating a computational telescope the size of the Earth,
p116
aVcapable of resolving structure
p117
aVon the scale of a black hole's event horizon.
p118
aVThis network of telescopes is scheduled to take its very first picture
p119
aVof a black hole next year.
p120
aVEach telescope in the worldwide network works together.
p121
aVLinked through the precise timing of atomic clocks,
p122
aVteams of researchers at each of the sights freeze light
p123
aVby collecting thousands of terabytes of data.
p124
aVThis data is then processed in a lab right here in Massachusetts.
