aa(lp126
VSo how does this even work?
p127
aVRemember if we want to see the black hole in the center of our galaxy,
p128
aVwe need to build this impossibly large Earth-sized telescope?
p129
aVFor just a second, let's pretend we could build
p130
aVa telescope the size of the Earth.
p131
aVThis would be a little bit like turning the Earth
p132
aVinto a giant spinning disco ball.
p133
aVEach individual mirror would collect light
p134
aVthat we could then combine together to make a picture.
p135
aVHowever, now let's say we remove most of those mirrors
p136
aVso only a few remained.
p137
aVWe could still try to combine this information together,
p138
aVbut now there are a lot of holes.
p139
aVThese remaining mirrors represent the locations where we have telescopes.
p140
aVThis is an incredibly small number of measurements to make a picture from.
p141
aVBut although we only collect light at a few telescope locations,
p142
aVas the Earth rotates, we get to see other new measurements.
p143
aVIn other words, as the disco ball spins, those mirrors change locations
p144
aVand we get to observe different parts of the image.
p145
aVThe imaging algorithms we develop fill in the missing gaps of the disco ball
p146
aVin order to reconstruct the underlying black hole image.
p147
aVIf we had telescopes located everywhere on the globe \u2014
p148
aVin other words, the entire disco ball \u2014
p149
aVthis would be trivial.
p150
aVHowever, we only see a few samples, and for that reason,
p151
aVthere are an infinite number of possible images
p152
aVthat are perfectly consistent with our telescope measurements.
p153
aVHowever, not all images are created equal.
p154
aVSome of those images look more like what we think of as images than others.
p155
aVAnd so, my role in helping to take the first image of a black hole
p156
aVis to design algorithms that find the most reasonable image
p157
aVthat also fits the telescope measurements.
p158
aa(lp159
VJust as a forensic sketch artist uses limited descriptions
p160
aVto piece together a picture using their knowledge of face structure,
p161
aVthe imaging algorithms I develop use our limited telescope data
p162
aVto guide us to a picture that also looks like stuff in our universe.
p163
aVUsing these algorithms, we're able to piece together pictures
p164
aVfrom this sparse, noisy data.
p165
aVSo here I show a sample reconstruction done using simulated data,
p166
aVwhen we pretend to point our telescopes
p167
aVto the black hole in the center of our galaxy.
p168
aVAlthough this is just a simulation, reconstruction such as this give us hope
p169
aVthat we'll soon be able to reliably take the first image of a black hole
p170
aVand from it, determine the size of its ring.
p171
aVAlthough I'd love to go on about all the details of this algorithm,
p172
aVluckily for you, I don't have the time.
