aa(lp174
VBut I'd still like to give you a brief idea
p175
aVof how we define what our universe looks like,
p176
aVand how we use this to reconstruct and verify our results.
p177
aVSince there are an infinite number of possible images
p178
aVthat perfectly explain our telescope measurements,
p179
aVwe have to choose between them in some way.
p180
aVWe do this by ranking the images
p181
aVbased upon how likely they are to be the black hole image,
p182
aVand then choosing the one that's most likely.
p183
aa(lp184
VSo what do I mean by this exactly?
p185
aVLet's say we were trying to make a model
p186
aVthat told us how likely an image were to appear on Facebook.
p187
aVWe'd probably want the model to say
p188
aVit's pretty unlikely that someone would post this noise image on the left,
p189
aVand pretty likely that someone would post a selfie
p190
aVlike this one on the right.
p191
aVThe image in the middle is blurry,
p192
aVso even though it's more likely we'd see it on Facebook
p193
aVcompared to the noise image,
p194
aVit's probably less likely we'd see it compared to the selfie.
p195
aa(lp196
VBut when it comes to images from the black hole,
p197
aVwe're posed with a real conundrum: we've never seen a black hole before.
p198
aVIn that case, what is a likely black hole image,
p199
aVand what should we assume about the structure of black holes?
p200
aVWe could try to use images from simulations we've done,
p201
aVlike the image of the black hole from "Interstellar,"
p202
aVbut if we did this, it could cause some serious problems.
p203
aVWhat would happen if Einstein's theories didn't hold?
p204
aVWe'd still want to reconstruct an accurate picture of what was going on.
p205
aVIf we bake Einstein's equations too much into our algorithms,
p206
aVwe'll just end up seeing what we expect to see.
p207
aVIn other words, we want to leave the option open
p208
aVfor there being a giant elephant at the center of our galaxy.
p209
aa(lp210
V(Laughter)
