aa(lp212
VDifferent types of images have very distinct features.
p213
aVWe can easily tell the difference between black hole simulation images
p214
aVand images we take every day here on Earth.
p215
aVWe need a way to tell our algorithms what images look like
p216
aVwithout imposing one type of image's features too much.
p217
aVOne way we can try to get around this
p218
aVis by imposing the features of different kinds of images
p219
aVand seeing how the type of image we assume affects our reconstructions.
p220
aVIf all images' types produce a very similar-looking image,
p221
aVthen we can start to become more confident
p222
aVthat the image assumptions we're making are not biasing this picture that much.
p223
aa(lp224
VThis is a little bit like giving the same description
p225
aVto three different sketch artists from all around the world.
p226
aVIf they all produce a very similar-looking face,
p227
aVthen we can start to become confident
p228
aVthat they're not imposing their own cultural biases on the drawings.
p229
aVOne way we can try to impose different image features
p230
aVis by using pieces of existing images.
p231
aVSo we take a large collection of images,
p232
aVand we break them down into their little image patches.
p233
aVWe then can treat each image patch a little bit like pieces of a puzzle.
p234
aVAnd we use commonly seen puzzle pieces to piece together an image
p235
aVthat also fits our telescope measurements.
p236
aa(lp237
VDifferent types of images have very distinctive sets of puzzle pieces.
